7 (1) A description of the property;
8 (2) The details of the sale;
9 (3) The reason for the transaction;
10 (4) The current fair market value of the property, including an appraisal unless
11 good cause is shown;
12 (5) An explanation of why the transaction is in the best interest of the person to
13 be protected; and
14 (6) A notice that any person interested in the real property of the person to be
15 protected must file an objection to the transaction within ten days of the
16 notice and demand a hearing.
17 b. The motion must be served upon the protected person, the spouse of the person
18 to be protected, and all interested persons those identified in section 18 of this
19 Act.
20 c. Consent of the spouse of the person to be protected or interested persons must
21 be filed with the motion. If the motion is unopposed, the court may authorize the
22 transaction without a hearing or may conduct a hearing and require proof of the
23 matters necessary to support the authorization of the transaction.
24 d. The court's order must include specific findings regarding whether the transaction
25 is in the best interests of the person to be protected.
